5
00:01:00,325 --> 00:01:09,436
But of course, what we're particularly interested in here, as I said, Ipanya, is our spiritual progress.

6
00:01:11,438 --> 00:01:15,263
And I want to start with a quote from Meichi Kao.

7
00:01:16,525 --> 00:01:18,507
I'm sure I've not pronounced that right.

8
00:01:18,528 --> 00:01:28,260
But anyway, she's a Thai forest nun who died late last century, 80s maybe, something like that.

9
00:01:28,460 --> 00:01:29,843
And she wrote an autobiography.

10
00:01:30,852 --> 00:01:39,905
And she was well, she was acknowledged as an Arahant.

11
00:01:40,305 --> 00:01:42,929
Fully self-awakened.

12
00:01:42,948 --> 00:01:44,771
Not self-awakened, fully awakened.

13
00:01:45,972 --> 00:01:49,278
And this is one of the core quotes from her autobiography.

14
00:01:51,740 --> 00:01:56,507
Body, mind and essence are all distinct and separate realities.

15
00:01:58,710 --> 00:02:00,352
Absolutely everything is known.

16
00:02:00,956 --> 00:02:18,491
earth, water, fire and wind, body, feeling, memory, thought and consciousness, sound, sight, smells, taste, touches and emotions, anger, greed and delusion, all are known.

17
00:02:18,512 --> 00:02:23,015
I know them all as they exist, in their own natural states.

18
00:02:24,556 --> 00:02:30,002
But no matter how much I am exposed to them, I am unable to detect

19
00:02:30,420 --> 00:02:35,388
even an instant when they have power, any power, over my heart.

20
00:02:36,949 --> 00:02:44,139
They arise and cease, they are forever changing, but the presence that knows them never changes for an instant.

21
00:02:45,823 --> 00:02:48,346
It is forever unborn and undying.

22
00:02:49,326 --> 00:02:51,150
This is the end of all suffering.

23
00:02:54,193 --> 00:02:55,096
I shall read that again.

24
00:02:55,735 --> 00:02:57,558
I think it's worth reading a few times, actually.

25
00:03:01,099 --> 00:03:06,324
Body, mind and essence are all distinct and separate realities.

26
00:03:08,526 --> 00:03:09,968
Absolutely everything is known.

27
00:03:11,250 --> 00:03:13,532
Earth, water, fire and wind.

28
00:03:15,373 --> 00:03:18,296
Body, feeling, memory, thought and consciousness.

29
00:03:20,078 --> 00:03:24,522
Sounds, sights, smells, tastes, touches and emotions.

30
00:03:26,384 --> 00:03:28,947
Anger, greed and delusion all are known.

31
00:03:30,731 --> 00:03:34,877
I know them all as they exist in their own natural states.

32
00:03:36,699 --> 00:03:46,188
But no matter how much I'm exposed to them, I'm unable to detect even an instant when they have any power over my heart.

33
00:03:48,472 --> 00:03:57,401
They arise and cease, they are forever changing, but the presence that knows them never changes for an instant.

34
00:03:57,421 --> 00:04:00,164
It is forever unborn and undying

35
00:04:00,854 --> 00:04:30,084
this is the end of all suffering so now we have to unpack this so that we can use it as a guide to our own practice first of all she says body, mind and essence are all distinct and separate realities so now when the Buddha finally sat under that tree he was driven by

36
00:04:30,334 --> 00:04:58,603
the question about suffering which up until then he had tried to answer through achieving happiness and in those days there were two methodologies one was either through the practice of jhana these absorptions which produce ecstatic states of mind i'm sure all of you have touched upon these states but unfortunately they arise and pass away that's what he discovered even though teachers of his time

37
00:04:59,055 --> 00:05:02,399
would have said that this is the highest and there's nowhere beyond it.

38
00:05:03,720 --> 00:05:05,822
And the other way was self-mortification.

39
00:05:06,622 --> 00:05:11,406
And the idea there was to liberate the soul, the eternal soul, from the body.

40
00:05:11,848 --> 00:05:18,372
The body being a manifestation of attachment to this form, this realm.

41
00:05:18,392 --> 00:05:21,096
So one went into mortification exercise.

42
00:05:21,196 --> 00:05:22,656
One gave up the world.

43
00:05:23,838 --> 00:05:29,062
But gave up the world in a sense that was to destroy the body

44
00:05:30,476 --> 00:05:37,283
And eventually, in the James sex, and I'm sure others, the idea was to starve oneself to death.

45
00:05:37,622 --> 00:05:45,430
And that was the final act of renunciation, the final act of self-mortification, which would then release the soul into heaven.

46
00:05:45,449 --> 00:05:52,677
So remember the Buddha tried that, and found it just to be more suffering.

47
00:05:52,697 --> 00:05:58,661
When he came to sit under the tree, the whole process had changed around upon itself.

48
00:05:59,197 --> 00:06:04,345
And instead of seeking happiness, he began to question how he creates suffering.

49
00:06:05,146 --> 00:06:07,470
And that's what led him to his insights.

50
00:06:08,310 --> 00:06:12,437
But there we have this moment of doubt, self-doubt.

51
00:06:13,257 --> 00:06:17,963
And it's something that we'll all come across, self-doubt.

52
00:06:17,983 --> 00:06:23,913
Who am I to sit here under the tree and work out this question which everybody else has been trying to do?

53
00:06:25,295 --> 00:06:26,877
And there's nothing special about me.

54
00:06:28,307 --> 00:06:37,375
And it's put in that mythological way that Mara attacked him with all sorts of sensual pleasures, boredom, all the usual stuff.

55
00:06:38,637 --> 00:06:40,798
But mostly this sense of self-doubt.

56
00:06:42,440 --> 00:06:51,108
And it was when he touched the ground, again, you know, in the mythology of it, and up rose the goddess, the earth goddess.

57
00:06:52,709 --> 00:06:57,454
And she stated clearly that the reason he had a right to sit there

58
00:06:58,379 --> 00:07:26,427
and cracked this problem was because of his past past lives through which he had exercised the perfection of generosity and that's the beginning of the bodhisattva vow in other words he wasn't doing it just for himself but for others and with that there came the strength to sit through the process of liberation which includes remember a process of purification

59
00:07:27,336 --> 00:07:43,355
When Mara attacked him, that was part of the purification, of letting go of all these desires and of coming to terms with whatever impurities were in his heart.

60
00:07:43,375 --> 00:07:53,648
In our tradition, Theravada tradition, the Bodhisattva vow is one who determines to become a fully self-awakened Buddha in order to liberate others.

61
00:07:55,872 --> 00:08:04,805
This was then extended to mean the idea was to liberate oneself in order to help others.

62
00:08:05,987 --> 00:08:11,336
And then finally, you wouldn't yourself become liberated until everybody else was liberated.

63
00:08:11,555 --> 00:08:12,718
Which is the Mahayana vow.

64
00:08:13,478 --> 00:08:16,103
Which always seems to me a little improbable.

65
00:08:16,884 --> 00:08:20,170
Because you'd be hanging around for a long time.

66
00:08:20,470 --> 00:08:24,276
And it's definitely not a determination that Siddhartha Gautama made.

67
00:08:25,353 --> 00:08:32,964
So I think it's best just to get on with it and become liberated with the intention that you will share it to others.

68
00:08:33,445 --> 00:08:35,206
And it's impossible not to.

69
00:08:35,607 --> 00:08:40,335
It's impossible to follow the path and not cultivate generosity.

70
00:08:44,660 --> 00:08:52,692
So when he sits under this tree, again we have it in the mythology, that he broke through the delusions.

71
00:08:56,081 --> 00:08:59,746
And three knowledges came to him.

72
00:08:59,767 --> 00:09:05,095
The first was that he was completely clear of these impurities.

73
00:09:05,414 --> 00:09:20,475
And the second one was that through recalling all his past lives, he saw that the key to that process was in ethics.

74
00:09:21,597 --> 00:09:21,717
Right?

75
00:09:22,102 --> 00:09:28,230
So just making a quick distinction between morality and ethics, most people look upon morality as thou shalt not.

76
00:09:28,892 --> 00:09:31,254
So it is a bit of a loaded word.

77
00:09:31,274 --> 00:09:33,837
But ethics just means relationship.

78
00:09:33,857 --> 00:09:40,047
What is your relationship to the world, including people, animals, etc., etc.?

79
00:09:41,067 --> 00:09:51,081
So through these past decisions, he moved from life to life until completely purified, or should we say ready to make this big break,

80
00:09:51,517 --> 00:09:52,938
He is reborn.

81
00:09:53,679 --> 00:09:59,248
But he also notices that other beings are moving from realm to realm according to the same conditioning.

82
00:10:00,428 --> 00:10:05,636
So what was a personal understanding of him, a personal law, became universal.

83
00:10:06,437 --> 00:10:14,688
And so in this process of liberation, there is both the process of insight and the process of purification.

84
00:10:18,937 --> 00:10:28,392
Now, when he then begins to teach, he makes this distinction between the body and the mind.

85
00:10:29,994 --> 00:10:31,015
So this is it, you see.

86
00:10:31,876 --> 00:10:33,960
Our separate realities, body and mind.

87
00:10:34,801 --> 00:10:40,109
Which doesn't sound very materialistic, scientifically speaking, correct.

88
00:10:40,249 --> 00:10:47,679
Because everything, as you know, from a material scientist's point of view, is an emanation, not an emanation, what they call it.

89
00:10:47,996 --> 00:10:51,061
It arises out of subatomic particles.

90
00:10:51,381 --> 00:10:55,969
Consciousness arises out of subatomic particles.

91
00:10:55,989 --> 00:11:02,717
So in Buddhist understanding, these two are different forms of energy, but they're not the same.

92
00:11:04,701 --> 00:11:16,197
And one of the distinctions we make in our practice, which is a vipassana insight, is to clearly see that the body is one thing and the mind is something else.

93
00:11:18,270 --> 00:11:47,501
so there's desire and the body moves somebody stands on your toe and anger arises and it's being able to separate these two processes that is your first vipassana insight the second one is to see that the one is always dependent on the other so that's the beginning of this whole process of deconstructing our experience

94
00:11:49,404 --> 00:11:55,214
And it's in that process of deconstruction that we come across what she calls the essence.

95
00:11:57,317 --> 00:12:02,264
Now I don't know whether essence actually translates her Thai word, but it'll do.

96
00:12:03,067 --> 00:12:15,726
Essence meaning something which is at the core of our existence.

97
00:12:15,746 --> 00:12:17,269
Something which is essential.

98
00:12:17,889 --> 00:12:47,778
the rest is not essential but this is essential so if we take it at that sort of meaning that is also a separate reality and in again later Buddhist understanding this the Abhidhamma they would talk about conventional realities which is the body and mind and ultimate reality which is nirvana in the Buddha's own way of expressing thing he was much more interested in the experience of

99
00:12:48,873 --> 00:12:50,294
of Nibbāna.

100
00:12:50,315 --> 00:12:58,648
He was much more careful not to move into the area of, well, what is it that experiences Nibbāna?

101
00:13:00,389 --> 00:13:07,561
It was more the sense of experiencing it and then a person deciding what his qualities were.

102
00:13:07,581 --> 00:13:09,683
In later Buddhism, the accent changed.

103
00:13:09,703 --> 00:13:13,789
It changed to, well, if there is this Nibbāna, something must know it.

104
00:13:14,552 --> 00:13:17,495
And so we get words coming up such as Buddha-nature.

105
00:13:18,606 --> 00:13:20,369
Okay, sort of a change of accent.

106
00:13:23,071 --> 00:13:32,500
So that was the first thing in our practice, in the vipassana practice, which comes down to us through the dependent origination.

107
00:13:33,100 --> 00:13:37,365
So this is the psychology that the Buddha teaches as to how we cause suffering for ourselves.

108
00:13:38,567 --> 00:13:44,131
And right there, he's stating that there's two different realities, nama and rupa.

109
00:13:44,952 --> 00:13:45,052
Okay.

110
00:13:48,644 --> 00:13:52,610
Then she goes on to say, everything is absolutely known.

111
00:13:54,231 --> 00:14:04,947
Now, when she says that, it's only what arises in consciousness at this present moment is known, meaning understood.

112
00:14:06,330 --> 00:14:13,119
It's not a case of just knowing it like it's there, like there are lights in the ceiling.

113
00:14:13,679 --> 00:14:15,562
It's a case of understanding what lights are.

114
00:14:16,284 --> 00:14:20,409
So in this sense, absolutely everything is understood.

115
00:14:21,150 --> 00:14:32,044
Absolutely everything is understood, not in themselves in a scientific way, but understood from a spiritual angle as to what they are in relationship to this essence.

116
00:14:33,807 --> 00:14:35,048
That's what's being understood.

117
00:14:36,311 --> 00:14:41,297
So this process that we're going through of deconstructing our experience,

118
00:14:42,086 --> 00:15:01,913
which means just unpacking it, just separating the bits, just seeing how it all coheses, how it all comes together into this experience of being a human being, that whole process leads us to discovering this essence.

119
00:15:01,934 --> 00:15:07,962
The delusion lies in thinking that we are this process, that we are this human being with body and mind.

120
00:15:10,206 --> 00:15:10,947
In other words...

121
00:15:11,230 --> 00:15:17,796
The whole of spiritual life sort of ranges around a crisis of identity.

122
00:15:18,677 --> 00:15:25,482
The who am I or what am I is the fundamental question beneath all of spirituality.

123
00:15:27,625 --> 00:15:29,046
It's a question of who am I?

124
00:15:29,806 --> 00:15:32,629
Or perhaps a little bit more accurate, what am I?

125
00:15:37,293 --> 00:15:39,414
Then she describes the body.

126
00:15:39,866 --> 00:15:42,711
So the body is earth, water, fire and wind.

127
00:15:44,474 --> 00:15:52,504
Not wind in the sense of flatulence, but wind in the sense of motion.

128
00:15:53,066 --> 00:15:56,490
So here we have these four characteristics.

129
00:15:56,551 --> 00:16:05,884
Now, this is where the separation of the body and mind become more obvious to us.

130
00:16:05,903 --> 00:16:09,789
When we talk about the body, we're normally talking about something

131
00:16:10,072 --> 00:16:38,730
physical something that we can feel and touch like my hand but when I ask what is it that I know about my hand you see rather than what I think I know about my hand then it becomes it becomes we become to realize that actually what we know about the hand is only possible through the mind so

132
00:16:39,131 --> 00:17:08,463
blood for instance there's blood coursing through my hand I don't feel it it's creating a certain colour of pink and red and all that but I'm not aware of it and I'll only be aware of my bones when I knock them so when we're talking about the body in Buddhism yes there is a physical body

133
00:17:09,372 --> 00:17:38,821
but it's how the mind experiences the body which is where the problem lies and the mind experiences the body at a feeling level through these four characteristics it's either through some form of heat through some form of movement some form of pressure or heaviness, lightness or some form of cohesion, stickiness

134
00:17:40,507 --> 00:18:10,142
and all of the senses have some combination of those four so seeing for instance would be mainly fire hearing is definitely at the sense at the point where the sound comes into the ear is pressure remember everything else is interpreted within the brain mind complex but actually there at the eardrum all there is are pressure waves

135
00:18:11,708 --> 00:18:16,574
At a more subtle level, we have sense of smell and tasting.

136
00:18:17,075 --> 00:18:24,404
But when we get down to that, you'll see that it's some form of these four characteristics.

137
00:18:29,731 --> 00:18:37,201
So the reality that she talks about of the body is, in a sense, not contactable by us.

138
00:18:39,505 --> 00:18:41,007
Except through the mind.

139
00:18:41,407 --> 00:18:43,330
Except how the mind actually.

140
00:18:43,371 --> 00:18:45,433
Senses and feels the body.

141
00:18:46,275 --> 00:18:47,036
So for instance.

142
00:18:47,636 --> 00:18:48,438
Your toenails.

143
00:18:48,979 --> 00:18:50,339
Every so often you cut them off.

144
00:18:53,825 --> 00:18:54,586
I mean think about that.

145
00:18:54,946 --> 00:18:56,648
You just cut off a bit of your body.

146
00:18:58,951 --> 00:18:59,794
And there's no grief.

147
00:19:01,675 --> 00:19:02,076
There's no.

148
00:19:02,376 --> 00:19:03,298
In fact if anything.

149
00:19:03,358 --> 00:19:05,701
There's probably relief if they've grown too big.

150
00:19:07,805 --> 00:19:08,705
And you haven't a clue.

151
00:19:09,086 --> 00:19:10,909
That at this moment they're actually growing.

152
00:19:11,480 --> 00:19:17,227
There's nothing, there's no way in which you can tell that your toenails are actually growing at this present moment.

153
00:19:18,528 --> 00:19:19,569
But we presume they are.

154
00:19:22,212 --> 00:19:22,292
See?

155
00:19:22,313 --> 00:19:32,005
So when you actually investigate what is it that you directly know or experience of your body, it really is quite minimal.

156
00:19:32,325 --> 00:19:33,086
It's quite minimal.

157
00:19:33,646 --> 00:19:35,608
And it's like being in a car.

158
00:19:35,628 --> 00:19:36,069
So...

159
00:19:36,421 --> 00:19:46,394
You're in a car and you feel yourself in control of it and you can feel the movement of the car and you can direct the car and put little lights on all over the place.

160
00:19:46,974 --> 00:19:54,484
But actually, you know, you have an image of the motor but you haven't a clue what's going on inside the engine at that time.

161
00:19:55,085 --> 00:19:57,087
And if the piston blows, that's the end of it.

162
00:19:57,868 --> 00:19:59,029
And you've no control over it.

163
00:19:59,651 --> 00:20:00,712
So it's the same with the body.

164
00:20:01,673 --> 00:20:04,518
So long as it's sort of motoring along, everything's fine.

165
00:20:05,157 --> 00:20:06,359
But then when your leg drops off,

166
00:20:06,981 --> 00:20:34,878
and then you think what the hell so the distinction here is the body is one thing and the way the mind knows it and contacts it is something else it's not they are completely distinct but they're obviously not the same but she is clear that there is earth, water, fire and wind which is movement

167
00:20:36,377 --> 00:20:42,747
and that this is the way we know the body through these basic sensations.

168
00:20:47,934 --> 00:20:59,332
Then she uses a different form of categories, which are the candas, the five aggregates, the body, feeling, memory, thought and consciousness.

169
00:21:00,272 --> 00:21:01,575
So here now,

170
00:21:01,926 --> 00:21:04,931
The Buddha is deconstructing the mind itself.

171
00:21:05,510 --> 00:21:09,256
So we've talked about the body and how the mind contacts the body.

172
00:21:11,057 --> 00:21:23,593
Feeling are those sensations in your body which are caused both by the body, such as when you stub your toe and it hurts, and those feelings that are coming from the mind, emotional states.

173
00:21:24,354 --> 00:21:25,394
Those are your feelings.

174
00:21:25,816 --> 00:21:27,478
They're all feelings.

175
00:21:27,711 --> 00:21:37,703
Even though we might have different words for them, like sensations, feelings, emotions and all that, actually, they're all just feeling.

176
00:21:38,665 --> 00:21:41,808
And the fact is that they're either pleasant or unpleasant.

177
00:21:42,609 --> 00:21:52,402
Even neutral ones, when we go close to them and really investigate, you'll see that they side on to either being ever so slightly unpleasant or ever so slightly pleasant.

178
00:21:55,707 --> 00:21:56,907
That's our feeling life.

179
00:21:58,711 --> 00:22:08,167
Memory, it's interesting that she translates, or the word sanya is being translated as memory, because the direct translation normally is perception.

180
00:22:08,749 --> 00:22:15,339
But of course our perceptions are like photocopies in our minds of things that we've experienced.

181
00:22:16,362 --> 00:22:22,692
And these photocopies grow the more that we experience the similar sort of event.

182
00:22:23,163 --> 00:22:31,109
So the more I eat apples, the more my idea of an apple grows, depending on all my experiences with apples.

183
00:22:31,770 --> 00:22:43,161
So what might begin initially as a simple perception then becomes a concrete concept of what an apple is.

184
00:22:43,780 --> 00:22:46,324
So I can distinguish between an apple and a pear.

185
00:22:49,826 --> 00:22:51,127
All that becomes your memory.

186
00:22:51,412 --> 00:23:04,807
It also includes all your words, all your understanding about various abstract concepts, art, freedom, democracy, all that sort of stuff.

187
00:23:04,826 --> 00:23:12,756
All that becomes part of your memory bank and words are a way of holding that understanding for us.

188
00:23:13,856 --> 00:23:21,164
So when we say a word like Buddhism, it comes up with a whole presumed set of understandings that we've

189
00:23:21,567 --> 00:23:25,351
what we've conjured up for ourselves through our reading, etc., etc.

190
00:23:28,034 --> 00:23:36,463
Now here it's translated as thought, but that isn't really a good translation for sankara.

191
00:23:36,483 --> 00:23:41,628
Sankara are those habits that we've created through acts of will.

192
00:23:43,371 --> 00:23:49,498
And there's a very clear understanding as to why the Buddha has deconstructed our experience in this way, right?

193
00:23:49,781 --> 00:23:57,230
There are other ways of deconstructing a human experience, such as Freud with his superego, his ego, and his id.

194
00:23:57,912 --> 00:24:00,015
There are different ways of looking at a human being.

195
00:24:00,455 --> 00:24:04,800
But this way is a way which is meant to help us liberate ourselves from suffering.

196
00:24:06,143 --> 00:24:16,415
And this particular sankara are where we actually have the power to change our relationships to the world, this ethics.

197
00:24:16,556 --> 00:24:18,979
The ethics is within these sankaras.

198
00:24:19,853 --> 00:24:32,410
And every time we've had an intention which is wholesome, and we have empowered it into a good continuous habit, we're creating these conditionings, volitional conditionings.

199
00:24:34,112 --> 00:24:37,696
And in the same way, something unwholesome, we develop that too.

200
00:24:38,317 --> 00:24:43,464
And what we discover is, by recognizing something as unwholesome,

201
00:24:44,051 --> 00:25:01,395
and allowing the power of that desire to arise and manifest as desire, not indulging it through our thoughts, through our language and through our deeds, allows that energy to exhaust itself and we undermine that particular habit.

202
00:25:01,936 --> 00:25:04,740
Eventually, it should be completely destroyed.

